Thread Life Cycle in Java
A thread in Java is known for independent execution. During its life cycle, a thread moves through various states. In Java, thread execution is controlled by the JVM (Java Virtual Machine). The JVM does not execute programs directly; it uses threads (like the default main thread) to execute programs.

The 5 States of a Thread Life Cycle
When you create a thread, it must pass through the following five states:

1. Born / New State
What happens: This is the very first state. The thread is created using the new keyword (e.g., Thread t = new Thread();).

Status: The thread is just born; it has not started executing yet.

2. Ready / Runnable State
What happens: To move a thread from the Born state to the Ready state, you must call the start() method on the thread object (e.g., t.start();).

Status: The thread is now fully prepared and ready to execute. However, it is not currently executing. It is waiting in a pool for the Thread Scheduler to select it for execution.

3. Running State
What happens: When the Thread Scheduler selects the thread from the Ready state, it moves into the Running state.

Status: The thread is actively executing its task (specifically, it is executing the code inside its run() method).

4. Waiting / Blocked / Suspended State
What happens: While a thread is actively executing in the Running state, it can be paused or blocked and moved to the Waiting/Blocked state.

Triggers: This happens if any of the following methods are called on the thread:

join()

sleep(time_in_ms)

wait()

suspend()

Recovery: A thread cannot execute in this state. It must return to the Ready State first.

If suspend() was called, you must call resume() to send it back to the Ready state.

If wait() was called, you must call notify() or notifyAll().

If sleep() was called, it will automatically move back to the Ready state once the specified time (e.g., 1000 milliseconds) expires.

5. Dead / Exit State
What happens: This is the final state of a thread's life cycle.

Triggers:

Natural Death: The thread naturally enters the Dead state when it has completely finished executing its run() method.

Forced Death: If a thread is partially executed in the Running state and you want to terminate it immediately, you can call the stop() method (e.g., t.stop();). This forces the thread directly into the Dead state.